<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: SPENDING CAP URGED IN AUDITOR'S RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rival candidate Richard Morrisset has called on Ventura County's appointed 
incumbent Auditor-Controller Thomas O. Mahon to set a spending cap of $15,000 
apiece on the race. 
</P>
<P>
 Morrisset, who will face Mahon in the Nov. 8 election, said the amount would 
be more than enough for each candidate to run a competitive race.At the same 
time, he said it would demonstrate their commitment to being fiscally 
responsible. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is a great way to show the public who can control expenditures," said 
Morrisset, who owns a Camarillo accounting firm. 
</P>
<P>
 But Mahon said the spending limit would only hamper his campaign, making it 
more difficult to educate county voters on the auditor's job and about him. In 
addition to monitoring spending, the auditor-controller prepares the county's 
payroll and budget. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you're running for office, I think you have a responsibility to do 
whatever you can to get your message out," said Mahon, who was appointed 
auditor-controller last year by the Board of Supervisors after serving 20 years 
as assistant auditor. CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
