<HEADLINE>
<P>
NURSE WHO JUMPED BAIL IN 1992 IS ARRESTED IN MEXICO; CRIME: SHE HAD BEEN 
INDICTED FOR TAMPERING WITH PATIENTS' INJECTIONS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Lomita nurse who claimed that she orchestrated her own arrest to get 
treatment for recurring headaches -- and who then jumped bail in 1992 and fled 
to Mexico -- has been arrested in Puerto Vallarta, the FBI announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Lissette Christina Nukida, 35, was arrested Thursday by Mexican authorities, 
the FBI and the United States Marshal's Service almost three years to the day 
after she was indicted by a federal grand jury for tampering with the 
intravenous injections of her patients, FBI Special Agent Charlie J. Parsons 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Nukida was accused by the grand jury of illegally administering insulin taken 
from a storeroom, causing two patients at the Casa Colina Peninsula 
Rehabilitation Center to suffer accelerated heart rates, increased blood 
pressure and dangerously low levels of blood sugar. 
</P>
<P>
 Although the patients recovered, Nukida was indicted after telling authorities 
that she had contaminated the injections so she could be sent to prison and 
receive treatment for her headaches, FBI agents said. In May, 1992, she was 
released on bail from the Metropolitan Detention Center in Los Angeles and fled 
before her trial, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Nukida was arrested along with her husband, Roger David Brown, 41, whom she 
had married while in jail. Parsons said the couple apparently fled together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
